: Implemented via `StreamInfoAddressFormatterProvider::withPort()` that extracts the upstream host address from `stream_info.upstreamInfo()->upstreamHost()->address()`.\n\nOther duration operators in the same registry (lines 825-868):\n- REQUEST_DURATION, REQUEST_TX_DURATION, RESPONSE_DURATION, RESPONSE_TX_DURATION, DOWNSTREAM_HANDSHAKE_DURATION, ROUNDTRIP_DURATION\n\nOther address-based operators (lines 1063-1182):\n- UPSTREAM_HOST_NAME, UPSTREAM_LOCAL_ADDRESS, UPSTREAM_REMOTE_ADDRESS, DOWNSTREAM_LOCAL_ADDRESS, DOWNSTREAM_REMOTE_ADDRESS, etc.\n\nAdditional metadata and state operators (lines 1673-1756):\n- DYNAMIC_METADATA, CLUSTER_METADATA, UPSTREAM_METADATA, FILTER_STATE, UPSTREAM_FILTER_STATE\n\n### Access Log Formatter Architecture\n\n#### Parser Registration and Execution Flow\nFile: `source/common/formatter/substitution_formatter.h` (lines 30-125)\nFile: `source/common/formatter/substitution_formatter.cc`\nFile: `envoy/formatter/substitution_formatter_base.h`\n\nThe `SubstitutionFormatParser::parse()` method implements a three-stage lookup process:\n\n1. **Built-in Command Parsers**: Iterates through `BuiltInCommandParsersBase<FormatterContext>::commandParsers()` (line 87). This includes the `HttpBuiltInCommandParser` for HTTP-specific operators.\n\n2. **User-Provided Parsers**: Tries user-supplied command parsers (lines 98-105).\n\n3. **Context-Independent Formatters**: Falls back to `StreamInfoFormatterBase<FormatterContext>` (line 111) which internally uses `getKnownStreamInfoFormatterProviders()` to look up stream info operators.\n\n#### Registration Mechanism\nFile: `envoy/formatter/substitution_formatter_base.h` (lines 112-136)\n\nThe `BuiltInCommandParsersBase` template class maintains a static registry of built-in command parsers. The `REGISTER_BUILT_IN_COMMAND_PARSER` macro (lines 134-136) creates a `BuiltInCommandPaserRegister` instance that registers parsers at static initialization time.\n\n### Default Format String\nFile: `source/common/formatter/http_specific_formatter.cc` (lines 445-454)\n\nThe default access log format utilizes multiple operators:\n```\n[%START_TIME%] \\\"%REQ(:METHOD)% %REQ(X-ENVOY-ORIGINAL-PATH?:PATH)% %PROTOCOL%\\\" \n%RESPONSE_CODE% %RESPONSE_FLAGS% %BYTES_RECEIVED% %BYTES_SENT% %DURATION% \n%RESP(X-ENVOY-UPSTREAM-SERVICE-TIME)% \\\"%REQ(X-FORWARDED-FOR)%\\\" \\\"%REQ(USER-AGENT)%\\\" \\\"%REQ(X-REQUEST-ID)%\\\" \n\\\"%REQ(:AUTHORITY)%\\\" \\\"%UPSTREAM_HOST%\\\"\\n\n```\n\nThis demonstrates the integration of HTTP operators (%REQ%, %RESP%) with stream info operators (%DURATION%, %UPSTREAM_HOST%).\n\n### Utility Files\n\nFile: `source/common/formatter/substitution_format_utility.h`\nFile: `source/common/formatter/substitution_format_utility.cc`\n\nThese files provide helper functions for:\n- Truncating string views (`truncateStringView`)\n- Parsing subcommand headers (`parseSubcommandHeaders`)\n- Protocol conversion (`protocolToString`)\n- Unspecified value handling\n\n### Summary\n\nThe access log operator implementation is centralized in the `source/common/formatter/` directory with a clean separation between:\n- **HTTP-specific operators** (REQ, RESP, TRAILER, etc.) in `http_specific_formatter.*`\n- **Stream info operators** (DURATION, UPSTREAM_HOST, PROTOCOL, etc.) in `stream_info_formatter.*`\n- **Core parser and framework** in `substitution_formatter.*`\n\nAll operators are discoverable through two lookup tables:\n1. `HttpBuiltInCommandParser::getKnownFormatters()` - for HTTP operators\n2. `getKnownStreamInfoFormatterProviders()` - for stream info operators\n\nThe architecture allows for extensibility through the `CommandParserFactoryBase` interface and supports custom formatters via extension registration.\n"
